@aljoscha: good catch, thanks. The code as it was written could stick all the records in one shard based on how the runner apportioned the keys after the GBK.

(The tests were correctly passing because we create empty shards in that case... which meets the documented semantics, but we can do better.)

I also cleaned up the use of randomness in `ApplyShardLabel`. Rather than assigning every element to a random shard, pick a random initial shard and then round-robin. Seems more efficient, better balanced statistically, and just as good.

@jbonofre @tomwhite @kennknowles @dhalperi please review, I'd be happy to hear your thoughts on my notes to this branch as well.
Thanks!

BTW, we should consider adding [WIP] tag to PRs so that Jenkins/Travis won't try to build WIP PRs. Apache Spark works this way and it makes sense.

@charlesccychen @chamikaramj @silviulica

Could you please take a look?

What would be your preference related to the typehints example? Exclude the files from pep8 check (all blank line checks) or introduce blank lines in between.

Yes, Travis is broken right now.

@tgroh is on it. We believe this is because `forkCount=0` propagates options across sibling children modules. PR #544 fixes this as a stop-gap.

I'm hoping we can fix the `forkCount` issue fundamentally rather than hacking the build.

The null comes from:
newCheckpoint = new Checkpoint<>(null /\* residualElements _/, null /_ residualSource */);
And, NPE comes from:
init(newCheckpoint.residualElements, newCheckpoint.residualSource, options);

I removed replacing nulls with empty lists to init() in order to make sure I don't miss any other cases.
